<span id="freeTextContainer9517057253956829342"><i>Anticipation! It occurred to him that his anticipation was more pleasant to him than the experiencing.”</i> <br/>― Patricia Highsmith, The Talented Mr. Ripley<br/><br/><img src='https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1449206287i/17251444._SX540_.jpg' width='400' height='235' alt='description' class='gr-hostedUserImg'/> <br/><br/>Highsmith is amazing. She alludes to Henry James, plays with Nabokovian style, James Cain&apos;s dialogue, and blends it all with a Camus-like modern existentialism. Plus, the goddess walked around with snails in her purse. Face it, pretenders, &apos;The Talented Mr. Ripley&apos; is an amazing psychological crime novel. This is one of those books which should be </span>
  <span id="freeText9517057253956829342" style="display:none"><i>Anticipation! It occurred to him that his anticipation was more pleasant to him than the experiencing.”</i> <br>― Patricia Highsmith, The Talented Mr. Ripley<br><br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1449206287i/17251444._SX540_.jpg" width="400" height="235" alt="description" class="gr-hostedUserImg"> <br><br>Highsmith is amazing. She alludes to Henry James, plays with Nabokovian style, James Cain's dialogue, and blends it all with a Camus-like modern existentialism. Plus, the goddess walked around with snails in her purse. Face it, pretenders, 'The Talented Mr. Ripley' is an amazing psychological crime novel. This is one of those books which should be used as evidence to highlight the case that some of the best literature of the 20th Century came out of genre fiction. The novel is high-wire, high-risk, high-reward masterpiece. It leaves me amazed the Cure didn't just write their existential anthem to Highsmith:<br><br>I can turn <br>And swim away<br>Or I can raise up my oar <br>Staring at a boat<br>Staring far ashore<br>Whichever I chose<br>It amounts to the same<br>Absolutely nothing.<br><br>I'm alive<br>I'm dead<br>I'm lying Tom Ripley<br>Killing a Signor.</span>
